{"key":"post-9868479","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9868479</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;yes i have been using a torch lighter and changing my scalpel blades between species&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Not necessary.&amp;nbsp; I use the same scalpel blade until it gets so dull I can't get the cultures to release.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It sounds like you're swiping too many spores.&amp;nbsp; If the print is dry, the bacteria should be dead.&amp;nbsp; All you need to do is flame the inoculating loop(NOT scalpel) dip it in agar to cool, and then touch your print and then swipe it on the plate.&amp;nbsp; You'll get plenty of spores that way.&amp;nbsp; If you try to get a lot of spores, you also get a lot of contaminants.&amp;nbsp; Always work right against the flowhood, in the very center.&amp;nbsp; Don't work the edges, and never open a petri dish that is more than 1&quot; from the face of the flowhood.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9868572</next>\n<prev>9868315</prev>\n<first>9868174</first>\n<last>18953568</last>\n<when>1235667145</when>\n<utime>02/26/09 06:52 PM</utime>\n</post>"}